thesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3412.topic&index=36>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Elaa’s suggestions for Shadowblade balancing 5/30/02</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> A 37.5% chance to swing with an offhand weapon IS a 37.5% boost to overall damage output<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->No matter how many times you assert this, that doesn't make it so.  You're going to keep going around in circles with this argument (of semantics, mostly) if you fail to recognize you cannot merely negate the effect of styles and poison.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> You bring up how your attack always has the chance to be blocked, parried, missed, or evaded, thus making the effect of the offhand percentage smaller. What you failed to take into consideration that the exact same is true of the primary handed weapon.<br>
For example, suppose you encounter an opponent where you can only penetrate his defenses 60% of the attacks. Someone that uses a single weapon would have:<br>
(1.00 weapon damage rate * 60%) = 0.60 weapon damage rate<br>
Someone using dual wield at base specialization will still penetrate only 60% of all swings.<br>
(1.00 weapon damage rate * 60%) +<br>
(0.375 weapon damage rate * 60%) = .825 weapon damage rate<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is extremely shoddy usage of math.<br>
<br>
Correct forumale would be:<br>
Primary_hand_damage = average_hit_primary * chance_to_hit_primary * chance_to_swing_primary<br>
<br>
Offhand_hand_damage = average_hit_offhand * chance_to_hit_offhand * chance_to_swing_offhand<br>
<br>
If average_hit_primary and average_hit_offhand were equivalent, and chance_to_hit_primary and chance_to_hit_offhand were equivalent, you could collapse the formulae as you have done, and make a linear extrapolation, but they are not.  Not only is average_hit_primary != average_hit_offhand due to styles increasing the damage output of the primary hand, but from my understanding chance_to_hit_primary is improved by many of the styles as well.<br>
<br>
What you have is a resultant formula:<br>
Overall_damage_output = average_hit_primary * chance_to_hit_primary * chance_to_swing_primary + average_hit_offhand * chance_to_hit_offhand * chance_to_swing_offhand + poison<br>
<br>
I've effectively &quot;hidden&quot; the effect of styles (and armor_type_damage_bonus) by incorporating them in the average_hit_primary and chance_to_hit_primary variables, but they're still there, and they're important coefficents.<br>
<br>
It should be completely obvious from the above that increasing the chance_to_swing_offhand variable from 0% to 37.5% does not directly correlate to a 37.5% boost in Overall_damage_output.<br>
<br>
I'll end with an admittedly silly example to drive the point home: If I swing my primary weapon 100% of the time hitting every swing for 100 damage each, and my offhand weapon 37.5% of the time hitting every swing for 1 damage each, is my offhand weapon contributing 37.5% of my overall damage output?<br>
 <p><B>Daniel DuBois</B><br>

